comment_data.body: I can repro this on macOS with IntelliJ IDEA Ultimate Edition (version 2017.1.3 RC)

@rxlabz, not sure if this is helpful for what you need, but the following workaround seems to work:

1. Right-click Project view > Open Module Settings
1. Click + > New Module
1. Pick Flutter + enter properties as usual
@mit-mit thanks it helps, it is better than creating a new project and then open the .iml as new module in another project ! :)

@mit-mit ooops this method seems to have another problem => ( I'm not sure of it is linked, but) after creating a module via the Project settings/+ Module... , it adds the android subfolder as module in my project 
![project_structure](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1397248/25946611/3b30d0da-364c-11e7-9eb1-8e644d7089e2.png)
cc @skybrian for thoughts on the android setup.

I'm not sure what we want to happen here from a user experience perspective? The underlying "flutter create" command actually creates a new Flutter project with two modules in it. (We are doing this from FlutterModuleBuilder which is a bit of a hack, but that's how IDEA does it.) The directories have a fixed structure and we do need both modules if you want editing Android files to work.

So maybe we need to figure out how to disable adding a Flutter module to an existing project? It seems unlikely to do what you want unless the project started out empty.

Another possibility (speculating) might be to have a "Flutter Android" module type that's almost like a Java module, and only allow it to be added to a Flutter module? I don't know if that's possible with IDEA's API.
@rxlabs can you elaborate on your use case for this? What is the relationship between the several Flutter "modules" that you would like in a single project?

@mit-mit since I use Intellij , I use projects as a workspaces where I put all my "linked" modules. I can have one or more main Flutter Application modules, separated dart libraries modules, separated flutter libraries modules ... each has it's own git repo, and they are not all in the same file tree, but in the same workspace. 

example :  here I have a main Flutter app project + a yzl_off_lib flutter library which I need ti keep separated, but which is handy to have in the same workspace. On the top I have a group of dart and flutter libraries modules that I use with in this project and in others...

Is it weird ? :)

![device_prefs_dart_-_yx017-protos_-____projects_ytbx017_protos_](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1397248/26010138/091c1c70-374c-11e7-8fea-9126a52e49b2.png)

I'd support @rxlabz. For those familiar with Eclipse terms: IntelliJ project is similar to Eclipse workspace, IntelliJ module is similar to Eclipse project. It's totally fine to have several projects in Eclipse workspace and it's totally fine to have several modules in IntelliJ project.
Thanks for providing details, the makes a lot of sense!

If we decide to support this we will have start doing additional testing, and probably change the `flutter create` command to have an option where it doesn't create the .idea directory.

Also the android.iml template should be renamed to something like projectName-android.iml.tmpl.

(And projectName is itself a misnomer here.)

Creating multiple modules should work right in the next release.

Creating a Flutter module automatically creates an "Android" module to go along with it, but it will have a better name that should show the relationship.

title: Empty project folder after creating new Flutter "module" in IntelliJ
